<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="xsl/overview.xsl"?>
<lesson>
	<id>6</id>
	<title>Shall we drink some tea?</title>
	<summary>
		<content lang="ja_JP">Offering invitations and suggestions</content>
		<content lang="ja_KANA">Offering invitations and suggestions</content>
		<content lang="ja_ROME">Offering invitations and suggestions</content>
	</summary>
	<description>
		<content lang="ja_JP">In this lesson we will look at how to invite someone to do something. We will also look at how to give suggestions.</content>
		<content lang="ja_KANA">In this lesson we will look at how to invite someone to do something. We will also look at how to give suggestions.</content>
		<content lang="ja_ROME">In this lesson we will look at how to invite someone to do something. We will also look at how to give suggestions.</content>
	</description>
	<example>
    <section id="1">
      <title>
        <content lang="en">Statement vs Question</content>
      </title>
      <sentence>
        <item>
          <japanese>
            <content lang="ja_JP">ビールを<b>飲みましょう</b></content>
            <content lang="ja_KANA">ビールを<b>のみましょう</b></content>
            <content lang="ja_ROME">Bi-ru wo <b>nomimashou</b></content>
          </japanese>
          <translated>
            <content lang="en">"Let's drink some beer."</content>
          </translated>
        </item>
        <item>
          <japanese>
            <content lang="ja_JP">ビールを<b>飲みましょうか</b></content>
            <content lang="ja_KANA">ビールを<b>のみましょうか</b></content>
            <content lang="ja_ROME">Bi-ru wo <b>nomimashou ka</b></content>
          </japanese>
          <translated>
            <content lang="en">"Shall we drink some beer?"</content>
          </translated>
        </item>
      </sentence>
    </section>
    <section id="2">
      <title>
        <content lang="en">Polite vs Plain</content>
      </title>
      <sentence>
        <item>
          <japanese>
            <content lang="ja_JP">今から<b>行きましょう</b></content>
            <content lang="ja_KANA">いまから<b>いきましょう</b></content>
            <content lang="ja_ROME">Imakara <b>ikimashou</b></content>
          </japanese>
          <translated>
            <content lang="en">"Let's go now." (polite)</content>
          </translated>
        </item>
        <item>
          <japanese>
            <content lang="ja_JP">今から<b>行こう</b></content>
            <content lang="ja_KANA">いまから<b>いこう</b></content>
            <content lang="ja_ROME">Imakara <b>ikou</b></content>
          </japanese>
          <translated>
            <content lang="en">"Let's go now." (plain)</content>
          </translated>
        </item>
        <item>
          <japanese>
            <content lang="ja_JP">今から<b>行きましょうか</b></content>
            <content lang="ja_KANA">いまから<b>いきましょうか</b></content>
            <content lang="ja_ROME">Imakara <b>ikimashouka</b></content>
          </japanese>
          <translated>
            <content lang="en">"Shall we go now?" (polite)</content>
          </translated>
        </item>
        <item>
          <japanese>
            <content lang="ja_JP">今から<b>行こうか</b></content>
            <content lang="ja_KANA">いまから<b>いこうか</b></content>
            <content lang="ja_ROME">Imakara <b>ikouka</b></content>
          </japanese>
          <translated>
            <content lang="en">"Shall we go now?" (plain)</content>
          </translated>
        </item>
      </sentence>
    </section>
	</example>
	<grammar_points>

<p><font size="4"><u><b>Grammar Point 1: The volitional verb form</b></u></font></p>
<p>The volitional verb form expresses the speaker's desire to perform an action, and can be used to make suggestions or invite others to join the speaker in an activity. Similar to other verb forms, each of the three groups of verbs has different rules for constructing the volitional form. As with other forms, the volitional form for group 1 and 2 verbs can be produced by regular rules, but the forms for group 3 don't follow any particular pattern.</p>
<p><font size="4"><b>1.1 Plain Volitional Form</b></font></p>
<table align="center" width="600" border="1">
<tr>
<th bgcolor="#aaaaff">Group</th>
<th bgcolor="#aaaaff">Dictionary Form</th>
<th bgcolor="#aaaaff">Volitional</th>
<th bgcolor="#aaaaff">English</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>1</td>
<td>行く</td>
<td>行こう</td>
<td>Let's go</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td></td>
<td>飲む</td>
<td>飲もう</td>
<td>Let's drink</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td></td>
<td>遊ぶ</td>
<td>遊ぼう</td>
<td>Let's play</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>2</td>
<td>寝る</td>
<td>寝よう</td>
<td>Let's sleep</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td></td>
<td>食べる</td>
<td>食べよう</td>
<td>Let's eat</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td></td>
<td>見る</td>
<td>見よう</td>
<td>Let's watch</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>3</td>
<td>来る</td>
<td>来よう</td>
<td>Let's come</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td></td>
<td>する</td>
<td>しよう</td>
<td>Let's do</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p>Group 1: The volitional form of the verb is formed by removing the final "u" sound from the dictionary form and replacing it with "ou".</p>
<p>Group 2: The volitional form of the verb is formed by dropping the final "ru" sound from the dictionary form and replacing it with "you".</p>
<p>Group 3: The volitional form of the verb doesn't follow any particular rule and must be learnt.</p>
<p><font size="4"><b>1.2 Polite Volitional Form</b></font></p>
<table align="center" width="600" border="1">
<tr>
<th bgcolor="#aaaaff">Group</th>
<th bgcolor="#aaaaff">Polite Form</th>
<th bgcolor="#aaaaff">Volitional</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>1</td>
<td>行きます</td>
<td>行きましょう</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td></td>
<td>飲みます</td>
<td>飲みましょう</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td></td>
<td>遊びます</td>
<td>遊びましょう</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>2</td>
<td>寝ます</td>
<td>寝ましょう</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td></td>
<td>食べます</td>
<td>食べましょう</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td></td>
<td>見ます</td>
<td>見ましょう</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>3</td>
<td>来ます</td>
<td>来ましょう</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td></td>
<td>しまう</td>
<td>しましょう</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p>As you can see from the table above, the polite form is simple to create for all groups of verbs. Simply replace the "masu" sound from the polite form with "mashou".</p>
<p><font size="4"><b>1.3 Suggestions and Invitations</b></font></p>
<p>Statements with the volitional form of the verb express the speaker's desire to perform an action, so they can be used as suggestions to another person. This form emphasizes the speaker's desire. Adding the question marker か softens this desire somewhat and turns the suggestion into an invitation.</p>
<table align="center" width="600" border="1">
<tr>
<th bgcolor="#aaaaff">Statement</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>自転車で銀行に行きましょう - "Let's go to the bank by bike."</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>リンゴを食べましょう - "Let's eat some apples."</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th bgcolor="#aaaaff">Question</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>自転車で銀行に行きましょうか - "Shall we go the the bank by bike?"</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>リンゴを食べましょうか - "Shall we eat some apples?"</td>
</tr>
</table>

	</grammar_points>
